**Not screenshotted — see spec sections above:** Tracker Sheet (§3), Confirm End Sheet (§4), Morning Recap (§5). These are modal overlays; the written specs in this README are the source of truth, and the prototype HTML will render them live if you tap `+ Drink` / `End session` / complete a session.

The Paper palette is the recommended default based on the user's tweaks. Dusk and Neon are alternatives — don't ship all three unless there's a theme-switcher feature.

## Implementation Notes

1. **Verify BAC engine first.** `src/lib/bac.ts` already exists; just verify the redesign imports work unchanged.
2. **Encode tokens into `tailwind.config.ts` before building screens.** Extend `theme.colors` with the three palettes (see below for how to handle palette switching with CSS variables), set `fontFamily.display` / `fontFamily.mono`, register the spacing and radius scales.
3. **Palette switching:** easiest is CSS custom properties on `<html>` or `<body>` (e.g. `data-palette="dusk"` selector), with Tailwind's `colors.bg: 'rgb(var(--bg) / <alpha-value>)'` pattern. Store active palette in the user-preferences slice.
4. **Build the Session screen second.** It's the heart of the app and exercises most of the design system.
5. **Fonts before pixel-tuning.** Fraunces' optical-size + italic is load-bearing for the aesthetic; installing them late means re-measuring everything.
6. **Simulated states.** The prototype's Tweaks panel has four "sim states" (`dry`, `midnight`, `overlimit`, `real`). These are useful dev-time seeders — port them to a debug menu gated behind `import.meta.env.DEV` so QA can reproduce each advisory state.
7. **Responsive cap.** Wrap the whole app in a `max-w-[480px] mx-auto min-h-screen` container so it looks intentional on desktop. The outer viewport can be `bg-black` regardless of palette.
